A ci-cd.yml defines how the pipeline operates with:
workflow name: a label to identify the pipeline
triggering events: specify actions to trigger the workflow
jobs: define the tasks (like building or testing)
permissions: grant appropriate access levels to resources in repo

sample:

name: sample-pipeline
on:
  push:
    branches:
      - main
jobs:
  build:
    runs-on: ubuntu-latest
    steps:
      - name: checkout code
        uses: actions/checkout@v3

What is the difference between a workflow, job, and step?
workflow: the entire yml file, triggered by an event
job: a group of steps running on a runner, multiple jobs run in parallel by default
step: a set of actions to be executed (sequential so a task at a time)

What is a runner and what does ubuntu-latest mean?
a runner is a VM requested to git for running tasks. ubuntu-latest means the uses is given as ubuntu-latest which will request  for a small VM with ubuntu of latest version to run the actions on it.

What is the difference between run and uses?
run will execute whatever given in it as a CLI command. uses will look for default actions in the github marketplace matching the mentioned one.

What does needs do between jobs?
needs is like an if condition to trigger the particular job usually pointing at other jobs (like wait for the successful completion of that job)

What is the difference between push and pull_request trigger?
push trigger will trigger the action when there is a push in the repo. pull_request will trigger the actions whenever there is a pull request (opened, reopened, synchronized as per the condition given here)

What are GitHub Secrets and how are they different from env vars?
github secrets are like a locker for passwords which we enter manually in the repo settings. it is fetched from the git only when required unlike env vars which is exposed as an environment variable.

What does actions/checkout do and why is it always first?
without actions/checkout, there will be no files inside the ubuntu system. so there will be nothing to run without checking out the files.

What is actions/setup-python doing under the hood?
it will call for installing python with the version mentioned in the ubuntu system.

What happens when a step fails — do subsequent steps run?
yes, other steps run even when previous is failed unless needs is used there. 
*wrong. 
By default subsequent steps DO NOT run when a previous step fails — the job stops at the failed step. 
You need if: always() to force a step to run after failure. needs is between jobs, not steps.

Why do we use dbt deps before dbt test in CI?
if there are external packages used, dbt deps will download them. if we didn't do dbt deps when having external packages, dbt test will fail. 

# 1. Squash last 4 commits into 1
git rebase -i HEAD~4

# 2. Cherry-pick a specific commit hash onto current branch
git cherry-pick <commit_hash>

# 3. Recover a deleted branch using reflog
git reflog (note the deleted branch commit hash)
git checkout -b branch_name commit-hash

# 4. See full history including deleted branches and resets
git reflog

# 5. Revert a specific commit without deleting history
git revert commit-hash

# 6. Create a branch, make changes, raise a PR flow
git checkout -b branch_name
git add .
git commit -m "change done"
git push origin branch_name
go to github and raise new PR from pull request tab. or gh pr create --base=(target branch) --head=(current branch) --title=pr_title --body=pr_desc